SWOF table:

-- Sw (water saturation): fraction of pore volume occupied by water (e.g. 0.2 = 20% water)
-- Initial Sw is 0.2 and increases during water injection.

-- Krw (relative permeability of water): increases with Sw

-- Kro (relative permeability of oil): decreases with Sw

-- As Sw increases: Krw goes up, Kro goes down.



-- No gas, but table needed because Flo is a 3-phase simulator 
-- Sgmax is setto 0.8 to have coherent data with SWOF
-- simplest table has been considered

-- The simulator requires a gas table, so dummy gas data is provided.
-- Sg             Krg              Kro            Pcgo
SGOF
 0.000000	0		1.000000	0.000000
 0.800000	1		0.000000	0.000000   /  


-- Oil  Wat   Gas
DENSITY of each fluid
   53   64   0.0624  /

PVDO,  Pressure–Volume–Density (Oil)
It defines how oil properties change with pressure

Pressure (psi)    Bo        Viscosity (cp)
   300            1.05        2.85  
   800            1.02        2.99
   8000           1.01         3
/

Column 1 — Pressure (psi)
The reservoir pressure at that point. The table gives three reference points: 
low pressure (300 psi), medium (800 psi), and high (8000 psi). 
The simulator interpolates between them for any pressure in between.

Column 2 — Bo (Formation Volume Factor of oil)
This tells you how much the oil shrinks when it travels from the high-pressure
 reservoir up to the surface. At 300 psi, Bo = 1.05 means 1 barrel underground 
 becomes 1.05 barrels at surface — the oil slightly expands as pressure drops. 
 At 8000 psi, Bo = 1.01 — the oil is compressed underground and barely expands. 
 The closer Bo is to 1.0, the less the oil changes volume.

Column 3 — Viscosity (cp)
How thick/sticky the oil is at that pressure. At low pressure (300 psi) the 
oil is slightly thinner (2.85 cp). At high pressure (8000 psi) it's slightly 
thicker (3.0 cp). For comparison, water in this model is 0.3 cp — 
meaning oil is 10× stickier than water, which is why water races through 
channels while oil moves sluggishly.

PVTW,water at reference pressure 6000 psi, viscosity = 0.3 cp (thin, flows easily).
Pressure (psi)    Bo      Cw (Water compressibility) Water viscosity in centipoise (cp).Viscosity (cp)
   6000           1.01       0.000003                     0.3                             0  /

--PVT oif gas for 3-phi simulator flow - MADE UP DATA
PVDG
   14.7   178.1   0.005
   8000   1       0.01
/

ROCK -  Rock Compressibility
Reference pressure. Compressibility
   6000              0.000001 
/


SOLUTION ========================================================
The reservoir sits at 12,000 ft underground.
Pressure there is 6,000 psi.
From 12,000 ft down to 12,170 ft → pure oil (170 ft thick).
Below 12,170 ft → natural water.
No gas cap exists.
Everything starts in perfect equilibrium — nothing is moving yet.
Then the simulation clock starts and the injection well turns on.

( Starting Conditions)
EQUIL

--    DATUM  DATUM   OWC    OWC    GOC    GOC    RSVD   RVVD   SOLN
--    DEPTH  PRESS  DEPTH   PCOW  DEPTH   PCOG  TABLE  TABLE   METH

      12000  6000   12170    0    12000    0     1*      1*      0   /
-----------------------

      Surface (0 ft)
     │
     │
     │  12,000 ft of rock
     │
12,000 ft ◄── DATUM (reference point, pressure here = 6,000 psi)
     │
     │  170 ft of reservoir
     │
12,170 ft ◄── Oil-Water Contact (OWC), above this point oil and under it water
-----
 GOC DEPTH (Gas-Oil Contact),RSVD TABLE (Dissolved Gas Table)
RVVD TABLE (Vaporised Oil Table), there is no gas

SOLN METH (Solution Method)
Tells the simulator which mathematical method to use when calculating the initial fluid distribution
 throughout the reservoir. Zero means the standard method — assume everything is in perfect gravitational
  equilibrium at the start, with fluids distributed purely based on depth and density. Other values would
   use more complex initialisation methods, but zero is almost always used.
